>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row"><a href="/wiki/Tongyong_Pinyin" title="Tongyong Pinyin">Tongyong Pinyin</a></th>\n<td>ma</td>\n<td>m\xc3\xa1</td>\n<td>m\xc7\x8e</td>\n<td>m\xc3\xa0</td>\n<td>m\xc3\xa5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row"><a class="mw-selflink selflink">Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles</a></th>\n<td>ma<sup>1</sup></td>\n<td>ma<sup>2</sup></td>\n<td>ma<sup>3</sup></td>\n<td>ma<sup>4</sup></td>\n<td>ma</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row"><a href="/wiki/Zhuyin" class="mw-redirect" title="Zhuyin">Zhuyin</a></th>\n<td>\xe3\x84\x87\xe3\x84\x9a</td>\n<td>\xe3\x84\x87\xe3\x84\x9a\xcb\x8a</td>\n<td>\xe3\x84\x87\xe3\x84\x9a\xcb\x87</td>\n<td>\xe3\x84\x87\xe3\x84\x9a\xcb\x8b</td>\n<td>\xcb\x99\xe3\x84\x87\xe3\x84\x9a</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row">example (<a href="/wiki/Traditional_Chinese_characters" title="Traditional Chinese characters">traditional</a>/<a href="/wiki/Simplified_Chinese_characters" title="Simplified Chinese characters">simplified</a>)</th>\n<td>\xe5\xaa\xbd/\xe5\xa6\x88</td>\n<td>\xe9\xba\xbb/\xe9\xba\xbb</td>\n<td>\xe9\xa6\xac/\xe9\xa9\xac</td>\n<td>\xe7\xbd\xb5/\xe9\xaa\x82</td>\n<td>\xe5\x97\x8e/\xe5\x90\x97</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<p>Note: In H\xc3\xa0ny\xc7\x94 P\xc4\xabny\xc4\xabn, the so-called neutral tone is written leaving the syllable with no diacritic mark at all. In Tongy\xc3\xb2ng Pinyin, a ring is written over the vowel.</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Intuitiveness_issues">Intuitiveness issues</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wade%E2%80%93Giles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Intuitiveness issues">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Due to the system\'s use of an apostrophe to distinguish <a href="/wiki/Aspirated_consonant#Chinese" title="Aspirated consonant">aspirated and unaspirated consonants</a>, such as in <i>p\xca\xbba</i> and <i>pa</i> respectively, rather than using separate letters like in P\xc4\xabny\xc4\xabn and many other Romanizations, such as in <i>pa</i> and <i>ba</i> respectively, many people have omitted the apostrophe in transcribing Chinese words and names, assuming that it was an optional diacritic.</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Adaptations">Adaptations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wade%E2%80%93Giles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Adaptations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>There are several adaptations of Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Mathews"><i>Mathews</i></span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wade%E2%80%93Giles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Mathews">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>The Romanization system used in the 1943 edition of <i><a href="/wiki/Mathews%27_Chinese-English_Dictionary" title="Mathews\' Chinese-English Dictionary">Mathews\' Chinese-English Dictionary</a></i> differs from Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles in the following ways:<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It uses the right apostrophe: <i>p\xca\xbc</i>, <i>t\xca\xbc</i>, <i>k\xca\xbc</i>, <i>ch\xca\xbc</i>, <i>ts\xca\xbc</i>, <i>tz\xca\xbc\xc5\xad</i>; while Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles uses the left apostrophe, similar to the aspiration <a href="/wiki/Diacritic" title="Diacritic">diacritic</a> used in the <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_International_Phonetic_Alphabet" title="History of the International Phonetic Alphabet">International Phonetic Alphabet before the revisions of the 1970s</a>: <i>p\xca\xbb</i>, <i>t\xca\xbb</i>, <i>k\xca\xbb</i>, <i>ch\xca\xbb</i>, <i>ts\xca\xbb</i>, <i>tz\xca\xbb\xc5\xad</i>.</li>\n<li>It consistently uses <i>i</i> for the syllable <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[i]</span>, while Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles uses <i>i</i> or <i>yi</i> depending on the character.</li>\n<li>It uses <i>o</i> for the syllable <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[\xc9\xa4]</span>, while Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles uses <i>\xc3\xaa</i> or <i>o</i> depending on the character.</li>\n<li>It offers the choice between <i>ss\xc5\xad</i> and <i>sz\xc5\xad</i>, while Wade\xe2\x80\x93Giles requires <i>ss\xc5\xad</i>.</li>\n<li>It does not use the spellings <i>chio</i>, <i>ch\xca\xbbio</i>, <i>hsio</i>, <i>yo</i>, replacing them with <i>ch\xc3\xbceh</i>, <i>ch\xca\xbb\xc3\xbceh</i>, <i>hs\xc3\xbceh</i>, <i>y\xc3\xbceh</i> in accordance with their modern pronunciations.</li>\n<li>It uses an underscored <i><sup>3</sup></i> to denote a second tone which comes from an original third tone, but only if the following syllable has the neutral tone and the <a href="/wiki/Tone_sandhi#Mandarin_Chinese" title="Tone sandhi">tone sandhi</a> is therefore not predictable: <i>hsiao<u><sup>3</sup></u>\xe2\x80\xa2chieh</i>.</li>\n<li>It denotes the neutral tone by placing a dot (if the neutral tone is compulsory) or a circle (if the neutral tone is optional) before the syllable. The dot or circle replaces the hyphen.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wade%E2%80%93Giles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="navigation" aria-label="Portals" class="noprint portal plainlist tright" style="margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;border:solid #aaa 1px">\n<ul style="display:table;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0.1em;max-width:175px;background:#f9f9f9;font-size:85%;line-height:110%;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold">\n<li style="display:table-row"><span style="display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertic